@NODE Purpose "Purpose"
@prev Disclaimer
@next Requirements

A few days ago I "managed" to destroy the RDB of one of my friends.
He had several partitions on his hard disk but didn't know the exact size
of them.
I tried to rebuild the RDB for hours, but it was impossible; I had to
reformat the whole drive!

This gave me the idea to intentionally delete the RDBs after saving them to a
disk, with the possibility to restore them exactly as they were before.

You can use these tools for at least two purposes:

1.) If you accidently destroy the RDB of your hard drive, you can easily
    rebuild it with the saved files.

2.) If you don't want that someone else gets access to your hard drive, you
    can delete the RDB; if you had more than one partition on your hard
    drive, NOBODY will be able to restore it without the RDB-Disk; except he
    tries several ten thousand possibilities :-)
    The funny thing is:
    After killing the RDB you can continue working with the amiga, until you 
    reboot or turn it off.

    This means also:
    If someone comes along and turns off the power, he will find nothing on
    your hard drive after turning it on again; funny, isn't it? :-))

@ENDNODE

@NODE Requirements "Requirements"
@prev Purpose
@next "Installation"

* Any Amiga with an SCSI host adaptor that supports the Commodore
  RDB (Rigid Disk Block) standard.
* "hardblocks.library" (distributed with my tools)

The programs have been tested on an A3000, an A2000 with a G-Force and one
with a TrumpCard Professional.

I see no reason why they shouldn't work on any other host adaptor.

The programs are of no use for owners of Evolution 2.2 - Controllers, as
these do not support the RDB-Standard (ever thought about an update?).

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Installation" "Installation"
@prev Requirements
@next "First Steps"

First, double-click on the icon "Install_HD". This will copy the
"hardblocks.library" to the LIBS: - directory and the program files to C:.
Next, determine the name of the device driver of your hard disk
controller card.

    Examples of popular controllers and their devices:

    manufacturer/controller           device
    --------------------------------------------------
    Commodore A590/A2091/A3000        scsi.device
    Old GVP                           scsidev.device
    GVP Series II                     gvpscsi.device
    Supra SupraDrive                  suprascsi.device
    Advanced Storage Systems Nexus    nexus.device
    Microbotics HardFrame             HardFrame.device
    ICD AdSCSI                        icddisk.device
    IVS Trumpcard Professional        ivs_scsi.device / IVS_SCSIpro.device
    BSC ALF2/3                        alf.device
    BSC Oktagon 2008                  oktagon.device
    --------------------------------------------------

My tools need the name as a parameter when they are called.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "First Steps" "First Steps"
@prev "Installation"
@next "Normal Operation"

After you have installed the files, insert a copy of the distributed disk in
DF0:, go to the shell and perform a "SaveRDB <device name> ALL DF0:". All
found units will be saved onto the disk in the form "<unit>.RDB". The same
files will be copied into the S: - directory.

Edit the "startup-sequence" of the disk and enter the right name of your
device in the line starting with "RestoreRDB".

Write-protect the disk, make several backups of it and store them in a save
place.

If you later reboot from the disk, it will automatically rebuild the RDB(s).

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Normal Operation" "Normal Operation"
@prev "First Steps"
@next "Syntax"

There are two ways to secure your hard drives:

1.) Insert the command '@{"KillRDB" LINK KillRDB} <device name> ALL' in your startup-sequence or
    user-startup. That way your RDBs will be killed each time you reboot your
    computer from hard drive. This means, that you always have to reboot once
    from your RDB-Tools-Disk before you can boot from the hard drive. But the
    advantage is, that nobody will ever be able to take away your computer and
    then have a look on you hard drives later. The hard drive will be 100%
    secured! This works, because once the computer is running, it no longer
    needs the RDB on the drive; it is stored somewhere in memory. I don't know
    where, but who cares? :-))

2.) You can enter the 'KillRDB' command manually from a shell or use a hot key
    tool to activate it. This way you don't have to use your floppy disk each
    time you reboot. But if someone turns on your computer while you are not at
    home or even takes it away, he will have full access to your data!

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Syntax" "Syntax"
@prev "Normal Operation"
@next "Known Problems"

     @{" SaveRDB    " LINK SaveRDB}
     @{" KillRDB    " LINK KillRDB}
     @{" RestoreRDB " LINK RestoreRDB}

@ENDNODE

@NODE SaveRDB "SaveRDB - saving your RDB(s)"
@prev "Syntax"
@next "KillRDB"

This program saves the RDB(s) of your hard drive(s) onto a given path.
It also saves the RDB(s) in the S: - directory. The files will be named like
"0.RDB", "1.RDB" etc.

Syntax: SaveRDB @{"<device name>" LINK "device name"} @{"<unit>" LINK unit}|@{"ALL" LINK all} @{"<path>" LINK path}

@ENDNODE

@NODE KillRDB "KillRDB - killing your RDB(s)"
@prev SaveRDB
@next RestoreRDB

This program kills the RDB(s) of your hard drive(s). It will only kill an RDB,
if it finds the corresponding RDB-file in your S: - directory. So if you
connect a further drive to your controller and perform a "KillRDB [...] all",
the RDB of the new drive will not be killed, unless you add the parameter
'FORCE', which will disable the safety check.

Syntax: KillRDB @{"<device name>" LINK "device name"} @{"<unit>" LINK unit}|@{"ALL" LINK all} @{"[FORCE]" LINK force}

@ENDNODE

@NODE RestoreRDB "RestoreRDB - restoring your RDB(s)"
@prev KillRDB
@next "Known Problems"

This program restores the RDB(s), using the saved files.

WARNING: I cannot check wether the found RDB-files belong to the drive. If
         you restore the wrong files, your RDB(s) on the drive(s) will be
         destroyed! Nevertheless, if you restore with the right files
         afterwards, everything is ok.

Syntax: RestoreRDB @{"<device name>" LINK "device name"} @{"<unit>" LINK unit}|@{"ALL" LINK all} @{"<path>" LINK path}

@ENDNODE

@NODE "device name" "Device Name"
@prev SaveRDB
@next unit

The device name is the name through which the system gets access to the
controller. See also @{"Installation" LINK "Installation"}.

@ENDNODE

@NODE unit "Unit"
@prev SaveRDB
@next all

The unit is the unit number of you hard drive. It can reach from 0 to 6.

@ENDNODE

@NODE all "The parameter 'ALL'"
@prev SaveRDB
@next path

If you call ALL instead of a @{"unit" LINK unit}, all found units will be treated.

@ENDNODE

@NODE path "Path"
@prev all
@next force

This is the path to where the RDB-files will be saved.
The best decision is to choose a disk drive (e.g. 'DF0:').

@ENDNODE

@NODE force "The parameter 'FORCE'"
@prev path
@next Syntax

Normally KillRDB will not remove RDB(s) that are not saved.
With this parameter you can disable the safety check.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Known Problems" "Known Problems"
@prev Syntax
@next Credits

Never use "RestoreRDB" with an RDB-file not belonging to the drive!!
You will destroy the RDB beyond repair.

@ENDNODE

